title: For Sale/Trade:  Stoner AR15 in 7.62x39: The friggin’ Kitchen Sink Deluxe!
postcontent: So dubbed “Kitchen Sink” because it has damned near everything on it EXCEPT the proverbial kitchen sink, this beast defies convention, convenience, and practicality, deferring instead to remote preparedness, Swiss Army Knife variety, and pure badassness! Boasting a weight of well beyond what you’d likely prefer, the Kitchen Sink Deluxe (KSD) combines opportunity, novelty, and picatinny for the sheer hell of it.  Starting with convention, this Anderson Arms lower leads with the A2 stock of yesteryear for a more sturdy recoil base and solid feel; of course, no set up for insane gadgetry would be complete without two (of a total of four) points for sling attachment! (The sling is a two-point tactical sling with elastic ends for picking up slack; the rifle provides up to four points of attachment.) The lower also has a Magpul pistol grip, enlarged Magpul trigger guard, enlarged/extended breakdown pins (a must when breaking down for storage!), a Magpul Battery Assist Device (BAD... get it?!?) lever for BCG catch release, and a FAB defense MagWell grip. Beyond all this combined application and novelty, this lower boasts the ability to accommodate not only the rifle’s 7.62x39 set-up, but also other uppers, including the popular .300 Blackout, 5.56, and more!The KSD Upper goes beyond the lower’s already awe-inspiring greatness by more than a stone’s throw by establishing a 12” quad rail platform on which to cram as much hardware as possible, going beyond rationale into an arena of ridiculousness! This circus of accessories only pretends - and only slightly and unconvincingly - to observe reason. Starting at the fore end, the uppermost rail (I.e., in the 12 o’clock position) has a light with a pressure switch drawn back along the length of the rail for ease of engagement at the receiver; a 45-degree offset front sight (for engagement of enemy targets (or paper ones) at varying distances) (to be used in tandem with the matching 45-degree rear sight at the aft of the 12 o-clock rail); a cutaway notch for the factory front sight/gas block; an attachment for sling mounting; numerous LaRue tactical rail index clips for ease of handling (to include several for the management of the pressure switch cable for the light); and a red/green MilDot reticle 2.5-10x scope with a side-mounted laser (for two additional target acquisition systems)! (Of note is the enlarged charging handle engagement lever for easier charging of the rifle.)Moving clockwise to the 3 o’clock rail (as you look down the rifle to your quivering prey), you’ll note the elegant simplicity of the next two items: an NVG mount and a LaRue handstop. (Both are cradled lovingly between the smooth contours of more LaRue index clips, bringing formidable fashion and ergonomic comfort to this juggernaut of excess!) (Note: The Armadillo device for the removal of the index clips is NOT included; hopefully, if you are considering this firearm, you have  the tools necessary (i.e., your fingers) to remove them yourself.) The NVG mount requires no explanation OR justification (NVGs not included, by the way); the hand stop, however, offers an additional support system for firing from the standing, crouching, or cross-legged position.The 6 o’clock rail exposes no surrendering underbelly’s weakness but rather three additional stabilization systems in order from fore to aft: quick detach bipod, front sling mount, and primary forearm grip (underfolding), the latter waiting underneath like this thing’s dong, held in reserve until action arrives and the KSD is permitted to spit forth copious amounts of hot lead; if used correctly, each promises its own reward, and the flow of the three roll smoothly into the lower’s aforementioned MagWell grip.The final, 9 o’clock rail is home to not one but TWO more stabilization systems, one which issues forth a hook for sinking into nearby trees, tabletops and door jams (thereby using pieces of the environment in which only fools would dare to face the KSD as a shooter’s bench), and the other a secondary (and five-position) forearm grip that extends right out at the 9 o’clock position for use with the 45-degree flip-up iron sights.Last but not least is the multi-directional, aftermarket muzzle brake, not the traditional birdcage, but perhaps the housing for something far more hellacious and sinister...Is all this gear necessary, or even reasonable? Probably not. Hell, each available slot is home to extra LaRue index clips, even. But when are words like “necessary” and “reasonable” pertinent in this hobby, brothers-in-arms? Do we need full-auto, 30-round magazines, or 1000-meter guns? Silencers, bayonet lugs, or laser sights? No. But we WANT them, and “need” doesn’t play into this KSD; this is an all-want piece of methodical shooting equipment, friends.
